document_data.Habitats:
Places in the Realms where gooseberries were known to grow included:
* [[Chessenta]];
* [[Cormanthor]], including around the ruins of [[Myth Drannor]].
* [[Cormyr]];
* Gooseberries grew throughout much of the [[The Dalelands]].{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2009)/Fruit in the Dalelands}}<ref>{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2013)/Deepingdale Politics}}
* [[Tethyr]], particularly in the [[Purple Hills]] region.

document_data.Usages:
* The [[bear]]s that inhabited the forest of Cormanthor particularly favored gooseberries and [[blueberry|blueberries]] over most other food.
* It was quite common for high-end establishments in the Realms to serve fruit tarts with a gooseberry filling as the first of two deserts in a full-course meal, what was known as the "First Sweet."{{Cite web/theedverse/2019-10-06 - Four-course meals of the Realms}}
* The [[High Flagon]] in [[Waterdeep]] offered its patrons sweet [[tart]]s with gooseberry filling.{{Cite dragon/302/Elminster's Guide to the Realms: The High Flagon|77}}
* The [[Moonstone Mask]] festhall in [[Neverwinter]] offered palm-sized gooseberries to their patrons. Elsewhere in Neverwinter, inns, taverns, and the kitchens of private homes often filled hand tarts with gooseberries.<ref>{{Cite web/theedverse/2019-11-25 - Neverwinter Cuisine}}
* Gooseberries were often featured in the mixture of wild berries known as [[Brackleberry jam]].
* Gooseberries were often used by inhabitants of Waterdeep in cooking a local delicacy known as [[melverfew]].{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2012)/Cuisine in Waterdeep}}
* Gooseberries were one of the fruits used to make [[Purple Hills Cider]].
* Gooseberries were sometimes brewed into a [[tea]] in [[the Dalelands]], the [[Western Heartlands]], and Waterdeep.<ref>{{Cite web/theedverse/2019-12-07 - Tea in the Forgotten Realms}}
* Gooseberries were one of the many types of edible berries in the Realms that could be used as [[material component]]s for the [[spell]] ''[[goodberry]]''.
